n Zhuangzi and dandyism, and Wilde wrote one of the first reviews of Herbert Giles's English translation of the Zhuangzi. Like Daoism, dandyism does not engage in a Confucian "correction" of language, instead preferring aimless roaming and rambling. The Daoist "carefree wanderer" is a flâneur, and both Daoist and dandy deconstruct the puritanism and correctness sought by Confucianism, Victorianism, and our contemporary neoliberal culture. Instead of seeking to induce correct opinions, they seek to liberate the mind.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 0aDandyism. 0aPhilosophy, Comparative. 0aPolitical correctness. 0aTaoism. 4aAsian Studies : Asian Studies. 4aLiterature : Nineteenth-Century Studies. 4aPhilosophy : Comparative Philosophy. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Taoism. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Taoist.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2023z978311149193640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143849453140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438494531423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438494531/original  a978-3-11-149193-6  SUNY Press eBook Package 2023b2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles